":"1375–1375","1375–Female":"1375–Overleden","1380–Male":"1380–Overleden","1382–1422":"1382–1422","1385–Male":"1385–Overleden","1386–Male":"1386–Overleden","1325–1429":"1325–1429","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1385":"1385","after 1409":"na 1409","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","About 1386":"circa 1386","1380":"1380","1436":"1436","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","1409":"1409","1429":"1429","1328":"1328","Cottesmore, Rutland, England":"Cottesmore, Rutland, England","Seaton, Rutland, England":"Seaton, Rutland, England"},"en":{"1355–1436":"1355–1436","1357–Female":"1357–Deceased","1328–1409":"1328–1409","1375–1375":"1375–1375","1375–Female":"1375–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1382–1422":"1382–1422","1385–Male":"1385–Deceased","1386–Male":"1386–Deceased","1325–1429":"1325–1429","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1385":"1385","after 1409":"after 1409","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","About 1386":"about 1386","1380":"1380","1436":"1436","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","1409":"1409","1429":"1429","1328":"1328","Cottesmore, Rutland, England":"Cottesmore, Rutland, England","Seaton, Rutland, England":"Seaton, Rutland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saint","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Lis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Stanislaw, Wladyslaw, Andrzej, Casimir, Ignatius, Malgorzata, Slawomir, Tadeusz, Tomasz, Boleslaw, Bronislaw, Darek.","Polish, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Polish and Czech dialect <i>lis</i> ‘fox’, Upper Sorbian <i>lis</i> ‘he-fox’, a nickname for a cunning person or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name. The presumably cognate Sorbian surname <b>Liš</b> is found in Germanized and probably also Americanized forms, only (see   Liesch   and   Lish  ). Compare also   Lese  ,   Lies  , and   Liss  .","Czech: nickname for a man with a bald pate, from a variant of the adjective <i>lysý</i> ‘bald’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lisak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Vyacheslav, Aleksandr, Yevgeniya.","Czech (<b>Lisák</b> and <b>Lišák</b>): nickname meaning ‘he-fox’, applied to a cunning person or a red-headed person.","Polish: patronymic from the nickname   Lis  ."]},{"name":"Lisiewski","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Slawomir.","Polish:","habitational name for someone from Lisiewice in Łódź Voivodeship, named with the nickname   Lis  ."]},{"name":"Lisiecki","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Genowesa, Irena, Piotr, Stanislaw, Urszula, Wieslaw, Wojciech.","Polish: habitational name for someone from Lisiec in Greater Poland Voivodeship or Liszki Łódź and Lesser Poland voivodeships, or Liski in Łódź Voivodeship both named with <i>lis</i>, <i>liszka</i> ‘fox’ (see   Lis  ,   Liszka  )."]},{"name":"Liszka","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Kazimierz, Beata, Czeslaw, Dorota, Halina, Tadeusz, Zofia.","Polish: from Old Polish or Polish dialect <i>liszka</i> ‘fox’, a nickname for a cunning person or for a redhead (see   Lis   1)."]},{"name":"Liesch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Ulrich.","German: topographic name for someone who lived in an area covered by reeds, Middle High German <i>liesche</i>, or a habitational name from a place near Trier named with this word.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Liš</b>: presumably a nickname from a shortened (masculinized) form of <i>liška</i> ‘fox’ (compare   Lis   1); alternatively, perhaps from a pet form of a personal name beginning with <i>Li-</i>. Compare   Lish  ."]},{"name":"Liss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avi, Morty, Hyman, Meyer, Mort, Zalman.","Germanized or Americanized form of Polish, Czech, and Sorbian   Lis   1 ‘fox’, and a variant of the same Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic) surname.","East German: habitational name from any of several places so named."]},{"name":"Liz","meanings":["Galician: habitational name from Liz in Lugo province, Galicia (Spain). As a Hispanic name it may also be an altered form of   Lis  . Compare   Deliz  ."]},{"name":"Lese","meanings":["Americanized form of Polish   Lis   1 ‘fox’."]}]},{"name":"Isabella","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the B